const Q_ENGLISH_2003=[{"id": "objective>English>2003>1", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the question that follows. </p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> When man evolved a conscience, his basic relationship with the other animals began to change. Until then, they were broadly divided into those which ate  <br/> him when they got the chance, those which he ate when he got the chance, and a third group which competed with him for food, or was otherwise a nuisance  <br/> to him in the business of keeping alive. <br/>  <br/> In the primitive situation, man was, therefore, basically against Nature but, as the battle was progressively won, conscience crept in; the  <br/> awareness of responsibility, and a failure to meet it, produced feelings of guilt. Those who live in cities and need no longer do battle  <br/> against Nature are nowadays most actively for Nature. <br/>  <br/> At this time, something like a thousand kinds of animals (vertebrate animals) can be said to be in danger of extinction. A few of them have been  <br/> reduced to this precarious position by extensive killing but the majority are disappearing only as fast as the particular kind of country  <br/> they need for existence is itself disappearing: and all this at the hands of man, as often as not by mistake. <br/>  <br/>  <br/> There are three species of turtles whose future survival is menaced by the demand for turtle soup, which would hardly justify the extermination  <br/> of a giant reptile whose family has existed for 200 million years. Leopards are in jeopardy because of the fashion for their skins. As they get  <br/> rarer, the prices rise and, as leopard skin coats become more expensive, the demand increases. <br/>  <br/> No species can long survive the price of ₦60,000 which a half grown baby leopard now carries on its skin. And crocodiles, the longest surviving  <br/> reptiles, are now dwindling alarmingly as a result of the fashion in crocodile skin for ladies' handbags and men's shoes.  <br/>  <br/> The human population explosion spreads mankind across the land surfaces of the earth at an alarming rate. There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead. Does this mean no room for wild animals? Of course not. With ingenuity and forethought, a place can be kept for them. To destroy their habitat is as unnecessary as it would be to pull down a great cathedral in order to grow potatoes on the site. A campaign to save what remains is the concern of a new kind of Noah's Ark  the World Wild life Fund. It does not believe that all is lost. <br/> <strong>Adapted from Peter Scott's article in Sunday Times</strong>. <br/>  <br/> The basic causes of the elimination of certain animals from the earth include</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man's decision to live in cities and the development of large farmlands</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">extensive killing of animals and the fast disappearance of their favourable habitats</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man's penchant for meat and the sale of animals for meat and hides</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a deliberate battle against Nature and the quest for leopard skin</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage discusses the threat to various animal species due to human activities. It mentions that some animals are in danger of extinction due to extensive killing, while others are disappearing as their habitats are being destroyed. Therefore, the basic causes of the elimination of certain animals from the earth include 'extensive killing of animals and the fast disappearance of their favourable habitats'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>2", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the question that follows. </p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> When man evolved a conscience, his basic relationship with the other animals began to change. Until then, they were broadly divided into those which ate  <br/> him when they got the chance, those which he ate when he got the chance, and a third group which competed with him for food, or was otherwise a nuisance  <br/> to him in the business of keeping alive. <br/>  <br/> In the primitive situation, man was, therefore, basically against Nature but, as the battle was progressively won, conscience crept in; the  <br/> awareness of responsibility, and a failure to meet it, produced feelings of guilt. Those who live in cities and need no longer do battle  <br/> against Nature are nowadays most actively for Nature. <br/>  <br/> At this time, something like a thousand kinds of animals (vertebrate animals) can be said to be in danger of extinction. A few of them have been  <br/> reduced to this precarious position by extensive killing but the majority are disappearing only as fast as the particular kind of country  <br/> they need for existence is itself disappearing: and all this at the hands of man, as often as not by mistake. <br/>  <br/>  <br/> There are three species of turtles whose future survival is menaced by the demand for turtle soup, which would hardly justify the extermination  <br/> of a giant reptile whose family has existed for 200 million years. Leopards are in jeopardy because of the fashion for their skins. As they get  <br/> rarer, the prices rise and, as leopard skin coats become more expensive, the demand increases. <br/>  <br/> No species can long survive the price of ₦60,000 which a half grown baby leopard now carries on its skin. And crocodiles, the longest surviving  <br/> reptiles, are now dwindling alarmingly as a result of the fashion in crocodile skin for ladies' handbags and men's shoes.  <br/>  <br/> The human population explosion spreads mankind across the land surfaces of the earth at an alarming rate. There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead. Does this mean no room for wild animals? Of course not. With ingenuity and forethought, a place can be kept for them. To destroy their habitat is as unnecessary as it would be to pull down a great cathedral in order to grow potatoes on the site. A campaign to save what remains is the concern of a new kind of Noah's Ark  the World Wild life Fund. It does not believe that all is lost. <br/> <strong>Adapted from Peter Scott's article in Sunday Times</strong>. <br/> From the passage, the attitude of the writer can be described as</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">partial</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">optimistic</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">indifferent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pessimistic</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This can be seen in the 5th and last paragraph. The writer is hopeful that the prevalent situation will improve.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>3", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the question that follows. </p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> When man evolved a conscience, his basic relationship with the other animals began to change. Until then, they were broadly divided into those which ate  <br/> him when they got the chance, those which he ate when he got the chance, and a third group which competed with him for food, or was otherwise a nuisance  <br/> to him in the business of keeping alive. <br/>  <br/> In the primitive situation, man was, therefore, basically against Nature but, as the battle was progressively won, conscience crept in; the  <br/> awareness of responsibility, and a failure to meet it, produced feelings of guilt. Those who live in cities and need no longer do battle  <br/> against Nature are nowadays most actively for Nature. <br/>  <br/> At this time, something like a thousand kinds of animals (vertebrate animals) can be said to be in danger of extinction. A few of them have been  <br/> reduced to this precarious position by extensive killing but the majority are disappearing only as fast as the particular kind of country  <br/> they need for existence is itself disappearing: and all this at the hands of man, as often as not by mistake. <br/>  <br/>  <br/> There are three species of turtles whose future survival is menaced by the demand for turtle soup, which would hardly justify the extermination  <br/> of a giant reptile whose family has existed for 200 million years. Leopards are in jeopardy because of the fashion for their skins. As they get  <br/> rarer, the prices rise and, as leopard skin coats become more expensive, the demand increases. <br/>  <br/> No species can long survive the price of ₦60,000 which a half grown baby leopard now carries on its skin. And crocodiles, the longest surviving  <br/> reptiles, are now dwindling alarmingly as a result of the fashion in crocodile skin for ladies' handbags and men's shoes.  <br/>  <br/> The human population explosion spreads mankind across the land surfaces of the earth at an alarming rate. There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead. Does this mean no room for wild animals? Of course not. With ingenuity and forethought, a place can be kept for them. To destroy their habitat is as unnecessary as it would be to pull down a great cathedral in order to grow potatoes on the site. A campaign to save what remains is the concern of a new kind of Noah's Ark  the World Wild life Fund. It does not believe that all is lost. <br/> <strong>Adapted from Peter Scott's article in Sunday Times</strong>. <br/> The expression <em>when man evolved a conscience</em> means when</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man developed an awareness of right and wrong</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man's intellect improved tremendously</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man acquired new habits</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man became a critical creature</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The expression 'when man evolved a conscience' means when man developed an awareness of right and wrong. In the context of the passage, this refers to the time when humans started to feel a sense of responsibility towards other animals and the environment, and feelings of guilt for failing to meet this responsibility. This indicates an awareness of moral principles, which is what is meant by 'conscience'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>4", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the question that follows. </p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> When man evolved a conscience, his basic relationship with the other animals began to change. Until then, they were broadly divided into those which ate  <br/> him when they got the chance, those which he ate when he got the chance, and a third group which competed with him for food, or was otherwise a nuisance  <br/> to him in the business of keeping alive. <br/>  <br/> In the primitive situation, man was, therefore, basically against Nature but, as the battle was progressively won, conscience crept in; the  <br/> awareness of responsibility, and a failure to meet it, produced feelings of guilt. Those who live in cities and need no longer do battle  <br/> against Nature are nowadays most actively for Nature. <br/>  <br/> At this time, something like a thousand kinds of animals (vertebrate animals) can be said to be in danger of extinction. A few of them have been  <br/> reduced to this precarious position by extensive killing but the majority are disappearing only as fast as the particular kind of country  <br/> they need for existence is itself disappearing: and all this at the hands of man, as often as not by mistake. <br/>  <br/>  <br/> There are three species of turtles whose future survival is menaced by the demand for turtle soup, which would hardly justify the extermination  <br/> of a giant reptile whose family has existed for 200 million years. Leopards are in jeopardy because of the fashion for their skins. As they get  <br/> rarer, the prices rise and, as leopard skin coats become more expensive, the demand increases. <br/>  <br/> No species can long survive the price of ₦60,000 which a half grown baby leopard now carries on its skin. And crocodiles, the longest surviving  <br/> reptiles, are now dwindling alarmingly as a result of the fashion in crocodile skin for ladies' handbags and men's shoes.  <br/>  <br/> The human population explosion spreads mankind across the land surfaces of the earth at an alarming rate. There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead. Does this mean no room for wild animals? Of course not. With ingenuity and forethought, a place can be kept for them. To destroy their habitat is as unnecessary as it would be to pull down a great cathedral in order to grow potatoes on the site. A campaign to save what remains is the concern of a new kind of Noah's Ark  the World Wild life Fund. It does not believe that all is lost. <br/> <strong>Adapted from Peter Scott's article in Sunday Times</strong>. <br/> Which of the following statements is true according to the passage?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Man kills animals only when he can afford to do so</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Man cannot spare those animals that eat his kind</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Man eats all categories of animals</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Man poses the greatest threat to Nature</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage discusses how man's evolution of conscience changed his relationship with animals. It mentions that man's actions, often unintentional, have led to the endangerment and extinction of various animal species. This is due to factors such as hunting for fashion purposes (leopard skins, crocodile skins), food (turtle soup), and habitat destruction due to human population explosion. Therefore, the statement 'Man poses the greatest threat to Nature' is true according to the passage.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>5", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the question that follows. </p> <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE I  <br/>  <br/> When man evolved a conscience, his basic relationship with the other animals began to change. Until then, they were broadly divided into those which ate  <br/> him when they got the chance, those which he ate when he got the chance, and a third group which competed with him for food, or was otherwise a nuisance  <br/> to him in the business of keeping alive. <br/>  <br/> In the primitive situation, man was, therefore, basically against Nature but, as the battle was progressively won, conscience crept in; the  <br/> awareness of responsibility, and a failure to meet it, produced feelings of guilt. Those who live in cities and need no longer do battle  <br/> against Nature are nowadays most actively for Nature. <br/>  <br/> At this time, something like a thousand kinds of animals (vertebrate animals) can be said to be in danger of extinction. A few of them have been  <br/> reduced to this precarious position by extensive killing but the majority are disappearing only as fast as the particular kind of country  <br/> they need for existence is itself disappearing: and all this at the hands of man, as often as not by mistake. <br/>  <br/>  <br/> There are three species of turtles whose future survival is menaced by the demand for turtle soup, which would hardly justify the extermination  <br/> of a giant reptile whose family has existed for 200 million years. Leopards are in jeopardy because of the fashion for their skins. As they get  <br/> rarer, the prices rise and, as leopard skin coats become more expensive, the demand increases. <br/>  <br/> No species can long survive the price of ₦60,000 which a half grown baby leopard now carries on its skin. And crocodiles, the longest surviving  <br/> reptiles, are now dwindling alarmingly as a result of the fashion in crocodile skin for ladies' handbags and men's shoes.  <br/>  <br/> The human population explosion spreads mankind across the land surfaces of the earth at an alarming rate. There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead. Does this mean no room for wild animals? Of course not. With ingenuity and forethought, a place can be kept for them. To destroy their habitat is as unnecessary as it would be to pull down a great cathedral in order to grow potatoes on the site. A campaign to save what remains is the concern of a new kind of Noah's Ark  the World Wild life Fund. It does not believe that all is lost. <br/> <strong>Adapted from Peter Scott's article in Sunday Times</strong>. <br/> The sentence <em>There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead</em> means</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">some increase in human and animal population growth rates</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mankind is fast spreading across the earth</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">many of us will die as a result of population explosion</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the population growth rate will double before our death</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sentence 'There will be twice as many of us before most of us are dead' is referring to the rapid increase in human population. It implies that the human population is spreading across the earth at an alarming rate. Therefore, the statement 'mankind is fast spreading across the earth' is the correct interpretation of the sentence according to the passage.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>6", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> The 2002 World Cup Competition, also called Korea/Japan 2002, kicked off with a match between the defending champions, France, and the Senegalese national  <br/> team from Africa. Nobody had given the Senegalese any chance against the star-studded defending champions but the 1-0 scoreline in favour of Senegal  <br/> showed that African football can no longer be taken for granted. <br/>  <br/> This shocking defeat of France had raised Africa's hopes of going beyond the first round of the tournament. So when the Super Eagles of Nigeria filed  <br/> out against Argentina on the morning of Sunday, June the second, 2002, many Nigerian football enthusiasts delayed attending church service to watch  <br/> the match live on television. As expected, the Super Eagles put up strong resistance to the Argentinian challenge and the day would not have ended  <br/> on a somber note for Nigerians if the momentum had been sustained throughout the match. <br/>  <br/> The hope of going beyond the first round, though precarious, was very much alive as the Eagles were expected to defeat their next opponents, Sweden and England. But some shortcomings in the Nigerian national team needed to be rectified to brighten their chances against their next opponents. <br/>  <br/> First, the defence needed to be strengthened to prevent the opponents from incessantly terrorizing the goalkeeper. Then the strikers also needed to  <br/> improve on their lack lustre performance against Argentina, since every Nigerian expected them to overwhelm their next opponents in the opening rounds. Lastly, rather than gamble with unfit players, a more creative use of the reserves would be necessary to smooth the way to the next round. <br/>  <br/> If World Cup debutants, Senegal , could nurse the hope of playing in the knock-out stages of the tournament, then the Eagles should soar instead of  <br/> being intimidated by big names, for no team is invincible. <br/>  <br/> Which of the following captures the writer's suggestion on how the Eagles could improve their performance in subsequent matches?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Better goalkeeping, a better attack and a stronger midfield</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Replacement of injured players, stronger attackers and a rugged defence</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Good coaching, more strikers and more defenders</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Fair officiating, good goalkeeping and fast players</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The writer suggests that the Eagles could improve their performance in subsequent matches by strengthening their defence, improving the performance of their strikers, and making more creative use of their reserves instead of gambling with unfit players. This matches with the second option: 'Replacement of injured players, stronger attackers and a rugged defence'.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>7", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> The 2002 World Cup Competition, also called Korea/Japan 2002, kicked off with a match between the defending champions, France, and the Senegalese national  <br/> team from Africa. Nobody had given the Senegalese any chance against the star-studded defending champions but the 1-0 scoreline in favour of Senegal  <br/> showed that African football can no longer be taken for granted. <br/>  <br/> This shocking defeat of France had raised Africa's hopes of going beyond the first round of the tournament. So when the Super Eagles of Nigeria filed  <br/> out against Argentina on the morning of Sunday, June the second, 2002, many Nigerian football enthusiasts delayed attending church service to watch  <br/> the match live on television. As expected, the Super Eagles put up strong resistance to the Argentinian challenge and the day would not have ended  <br/> on a somber note for Nigerians if the momentum had been sustained throughout the match. <br/>  <br/> The hope of going beyond the first round, though precarious, was very much alive as the Eagles were expected to defeat their next opponents, Sweden and England. But some shortcomings in the Nigerian national team needed to be rectified to brighten their chances against their next opponents. <br/>  <br/> First, the defence needed to be strengthened to prevent the opponents from incessantly terrorizing the goalkeeper. Then the strikers also needed to  <br/> improve on their lack lustre performance against Argentina, since every Nigerian expected them to overwhelm their next opponents in the opening rounds. Lastly, rather than gamble with unfit players, a more creative use of the reserves would be necessary to smooth the way to the next round. <br/>  <br/> If World Cup debutants, Senegal , could nurse the hope of playing in the knock-out stages of the tournament, then the Eagles should soar instead of  <br/> being intimidated by big names, for no team is invincible. <br/> A suitable title for this passage is</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">African Teams in the 2002 World Cup</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The FIFA Korea/Japan 2002</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Nigerian and the Senegalese Teams</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The Eagles in World Cup 2002</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage discusses the performance of the Nigerian national team, the Super Eagles, in the 2002 World Cup. It also provides suggestions on how the team could improve their performance in subsequent matches. Therefore, the most suitable title for this passage is 'The Eagles in World Cup 2002', which is the fourth option.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>8", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> The 2002 World Cup Competition, also called Korea/Japan 2002, kicked off with a match between the defending champions, France, and the Senegalese national  <br/> team from Africa. Nobody had given the Senegalese any chance against the star-studded defending champions but the 1-0 scoreline in favour of Senegal  <br/> showed that African football can no longer be taken for granted. <br/>  <br/> This shocking defeat of France had raised Africa's hopes of going beyond the first round of the tournament. So when the Super Eagles of Nigeria filed  <br/> out against Argentina on the morning of Sunday, June the second, 2002, many Nigerian football enthusiasts delayed attending church service to watch  <br/> the match live on television. As expected, the Super Eagles put up strong resistance to the Argentinian challenge and the day would not have ended  <br/> on a somber note for Nigerians if the momentum had been sustained throughout the match. <br/>  <br/> The hope of going beyond the first round, though precarious, was very much alive as the Eagles were expected to defeat their next opponents, Sweden and England. But some shortcomings in the Nigerian national team needed to be rectified to brighten their chances against their next opponents. <br/>  <br/> First, the defence needed to be strengthened to prevent the opponents from incessantly terrorizing the goalkeeper. Then the strikers also needed to  <br/> improve on their lack lustre performance against Argentina, since every Nigerian expected them to overwhelm their next opponents in the opening rounds. Lastly, rather than gamble with unfit players, a more creative use of the reserves would be necessary to smooth the way to the next round. <br/>  <br/> If World Cup debutants, Senegal , could nurse the hope of playing in the knock-out stages of the tournament, then the Eagles should soar instead of  <br/> being intimidated by big names, for no team is invincible. <br/> From the argument in the last paragraph, it can be concluded that the Eagles were</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">more experienced than the Senegalese team</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not as strong as the Senegalese team</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">more timid and goal-shy than their opponents</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">not sure of getting to the next round of the tournament</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From the last paragraph, it can be inferred that the Eagles were not as strong as the Senegalese team. The passage states that if Senegal, who were debutants, could hope to play in the knock-out stages, then the Eagles should also be able to do so. This implies that the Eagles were not performing as well as the Senegalese team.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>9", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> The 2002 World Cup Competition, also called Korea/Japan 2002, kicked off with a match between the defending champions, France, and the Senegalese national  <br/> team from Africa. Nobody had given the Senegalese any chance against the star-studded defending champions but the 1-0 scoreline in favour of Senegal  <br/> showed that African football can no longer be taken for granted. <br/>  <br/> This shocking defeat of France had raised Africa's hopes of going beyond the first round of the tournament. So when the Super Eagles of Nigeria filed  <br/> out against Argentina on the morning of Sunday, June the second, 2002, many Nigerian football enthusiasts delayed attending church service to watch  <br/> the match live on television. As expected, the Super Eagles put up strong resistance to the Argentinian challenge and the day would not have ended  <br/> on a somber note for Nigerians if the momentum had been sustained throughout the match. <br/>  <br/> The hope of going beyond the first round, though precarious, was very much alive as the Eagles were expected to defeat their next opponents, Sweden and England. But some shortcomings in the Nigerian national team needed to be rectified to brighten their chances against their next opponents. <br/>  <br/> First, the defence needed to be strengthened to prevent the opponents from incessantly terrorizing the goalkeeper. Then the strikers also needed to  <br/> improve on their lack lustre performance against Argentina, since every Nigerian expected them to overwhelm their next opponents in the opening rounds. Lastly, rather than gamble with unfit players, a more creative use of the reserves would be necessary to smooth the way to the next round. <br/>  <br/> If World Cup debutants, Senegal , could nurse the hope of playing in the knock-out stages of the tournament, then the Eagles should soar instead of  <br/> being intimidated by big names, for no team is invincible. <br/> The word \"debutants\", as used in the passage, means</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hard-fighters </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">under-dogs </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">first-timers </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">giant killers</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Debut means a performer's first-time performance to an audience. In this passage, Debutants will mean a country's first -time appearance at the world cup.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>10", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE II  <br/>  <br/> The 2002 World Cup Competition, also called Korea/Japan 2002, kicked off with a match between the defending champions, France, and the Senegalese national  <br/> team from Africa. Nobody had given the Senegalese any chance against the star-studded defending champions but the 1-0 scoreline in favour of Senegal  <br/> showed that African football can no longer be taken for granted. <br/>  <br/> This shocking defeat of France had raised Africa's hopes of going beyond the first round of the tournament. So when the Super Eagles of Nigeria filed  <br/> out against Argentina on the morning of Sunday, June the second, 2002, many Nigerian football enthusiasts delayed attending church service to watch  <br/> the match live on television. As expected, the Super Eagles put up strong resistance to the Argentinian challenge and the day would not have ended  <br/> on a somber note for Nigerians if the momentum had been sustained throughout the match. <br/>  <br/> The hope of going beyond the first round, though precarious, was very much alive as the Eagles were expected to defeat their next opponents, Sweden and England. But some shortcomings in the Nigerian national team needed to be rectified to brighten their chances against their next opponents. <br/>  <br/> First, the defence needed to be strengthened to prevent the opponents from incessantly terrorizing the goalkeeper. Then the strikers also needed to  <br/> improve on their lack lustre performance against Argentina, since every Nigerian expected them to overwhelm their next opponents in the opening rounds. Lastly, rather than gamble with unfit players, a more creative use of the reserves would be necessary to smooth the way to the next round. <br/>  <br/> If World Cup debutants, Senegal , could nurse the hope of playing in the knock-out stages of the tournament, then the Eagles should soar instead of  <br/> being intimidated by big names, for no team is invincible. <br/> From the passage, it can be concluded that the writer</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was optimistic about the chances of the Eagles</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">did not fancy the Eagles' chances</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was non-committal about the chances of the Eagles</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was certain about the Eagles' chances.</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The writer expresses optimism about the chances of the Eagles. This is evident in the passage where the writer mentions that the Eagles should soar instead of being intimidated by big names, for no team is invincible. The writer also mentions that the hope of going beyond the first round, though precarious, was very much alive as the Eagles were expected to defeat their next opponents, Sweden and England. This shows that the writer was optimistic about the Eagles' chances.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>11", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> Attitudes towards the smoking of cigarettes and the consumption of alcohol may be used to illustrate typical African ethics. Apart from the fact that smoking has now been linked with lung cancer disease, the African moralist has always regarded smoking as an indication of moral degradation. A number of people have accepted the moralist idea on smoking. <br/>  <br/> Some have refrained from smoking, and those who could influence others, such as parents and religious leaders, have also exerted their influence to  <br/> prevent others from smoking. On the other hand, a good many people have remained indifferent to the moralist view and have continued to smoke. The same argument has been applied to the consumption of alcohol. The African moralist, basing his judgement on the behaviour of a few alcoholics, tends to regard the habit of taking alcohol as a sign of wretchedness. The moralist holds the view that anybody who forms the habit of consuming alcohol will never do well in life. While this may be true in respect of a few people in the society, the fear of the moralist has not been justified. However, the economist is primarily interested in the habit of smoking and the consumption of alcohol in so far as they give satisfaction to smokers and drinkers and so generate supply of and demand for tobacco and alcohol. The economist is interested in knowing how many packets of cigarettes are consumed and to what extent an increase or fall in consumption could affect production, that is, supply. Similarly, he is interested in how much beer is consumed and how the supply of beer will adjust to the demand for it. He examines the habits and the pressures which can lead to the readjustment of wants and the reallocation of resources to cover the wants. <br/>  <br/> Some moral principles associated with religion tend to lead on to economic problems. Followers of certain religions are expected not to consume  <br/> pork, take alcohol or smoke tobacco. Devotees of some religious groups, on the other hand, can eat pork while others are expected to abstain from  <br/> alcohol and smoking. Strict observance of these moral rules could cripple the breweries, the cigarette factories and some businesses. However, there  <br/> seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers' a development which should be of interest to the economist. <br/>  <br/> The positions maintained by the moralist and the economist can be described as being</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">at variance </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">very agreeable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">quite indifferent</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">very passionate</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This can be seen in the 2nd paragraph. While the <em>moralist</em> is in opposition, the <em>economist</em> is in support due to its economic benefits</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>12", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> Attitudes towards the smoking of cigarettes and the consumption of alcohol may be used to illustrate typical African ethics. Apart from the fact that smoking has now been linked with lung cancer disease, the African moralist has always regarded smoking as an indication of moral degradation. A number of people have accepted the moralist idea on smoking. <br/>  <br/> Some have refrained from smoking, and those who could influence others, such as parents and religious leaders, have also exerted their influence to  <br/> prevent others from smoking. On the other hand, a good many people have remained indifferent to the moralist view and have continued to smoke. The same argument has been applied to the consumption of alcohol. The African moralist, basing his judgement on the behaviour of a few alcoholics, tends to regard the habit of taking alcohol as a sign of wretchedness. The moralist holds the view that anybody who forms the habit of consuming alcohol will never do well in life. While this may be true in respect of a few people in the society, the fear of the moralist has not been justified. However, the economist is primarily interested in the habit of smoking and the consumption of alcohol in so far as they give satisfaction to smokers and drinkers and so generate supply of and demand for tobacco and alcohol. The economist is interested in knowing how many packets of cigarettes are consumed and to what extent an increase or fall in consumption could affect production, that is, supply. Similarly, he is interested in how much beer is consumed and how the supply of beer will adjust to the demand for it. He examines the habits and the pressures which can lead to the readjustment of wants and the reallocation of resources to cover the wants. <br/>  <br/> Some moral principles associated with religion tend to lead on to economic problems. Followers of certain religions are expected not to consume  <br/> pork, take alcohol or smoke tobacco. Devotees of some religious groups, on the other hand, can eat pork while others are expected to abstain from  <br/> alcohol and smoking. Strict observance of these moral rules could cripple the breweries, the cigarette factories and some businesses. However, there  <br/> seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers' a development which should be of interest to the economist. <br/> Which of the following statements is true according to the passage?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">People who drink or smoke surely die of cancer</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Everyone ignores the moralist view on drinking and smoking</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Smoking and drinking may have positive effects on the economy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Total abstinence from drinking and smoking is a religious obligation</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">This can be seen in the 3rd paragraph. <br/> <em>However, there seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers' a development which should be of interest to the economist</em>.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>13", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> Attitudes towards the smoking of cigarettes and the consumption of alcohol may be used to illustrate typical African ethics. Apart from the fact that smoking has now been linked with lung cancer disease, the African moralist has always regarded smoking as an indication of moral degradation. A number of people have accepted the moralist idea on smoking. <br/>  <br/> Some have refrained from smoking, and those who could influence others, such as parents and religious leaders, have also exerted their influence to  <br/> prevent others from smoking. On the other hand, a good many people have remained indifferent to the moralist view and have continued to smoke. The same argument has been applied to the consumption of alcohol. The African moralist, basing his judgement on the behaviour of a few alcoholics, tends to regard the habit of taking alcohol as a sign of wretchedness. The moralist holds the view that anybody who forms the habit of consuming alcohol will never do well in life. While this may be true in respect of a few people in the society, the fear of the moralist has not been justified. However, the economist is primarily interested in the habit of smoking and the consumption of alcohol in so far as they give satisfaction to smokers and drinkers and so generate supply of and demand for tobacco and alcohol. The economist is interested in knowing how many packets of cigarettes are consumed and to what extent an increase or fall in consumption could affect production, that is, supply. Similarly, he is interested in how much beer is consumed and how the supply of beer will adjust to the demand for it. He examines the habits and the pressures which can lead to the readjustment of wants and the reallocation of resources to cover the wants. <br/>  <br/> Some moral principles associated with religion tend to lead on to economic problems. Followers of certain religions are expected not to consume  <br/> pork, take alcohol or smoke tobacco. Devotees of some religious groups, on the other hand, can eat pork while others are expected to abstain from  <br/> alcohol and smoking. Strict observance of these moral rules could cripple the breweries, the cigarette factories and some businesses. However, there  <br/> seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers' a development which should be of interest to the economist. <br/> It can be concluded from the passage that morality, religion and economy are</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">clearly interconnected</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">certainly different</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">somewhat interconnected </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">certainly unrelated</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage discusses the interplay between morality, religion, and economy in the context of smoking and drinking. It mentions that moral and religious views on these habits can influence their consumption, which in turn affects the economy. This shows that these three aspects are clearly interconnected. Therefore, option 1 is correct.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>14", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> Attitudes towards the smoking of cigarettes and the consumption of alcohol may be used to illustrate typical African ethics. Apart from the fact that smoking has now been linked with lung cancer disease, the African moralist has always regarded smoking as an indication of moral degradation. A number of people have accepted the moralist idea on smoking. <br/>  <br/> Some have refrained from smoking, and those who could influence others, such as parents and religious leaders, have also exerted their influence to  <br/> prevent others from smoking. On the other hand, a good many people have remained indifferent to the moralist view and have continued to smoke. The same argument has been applied to the consumption of alcohol. The African moralist, basing his judgement on the behaviour of a few alcoholics, tends to regard the habit of taking alcohol as a sign of wretchedness. The moralist holds the view that anybody who forms the habit of consuming alcohol will never do well in life. While this may be true in respect of a few people in the society, the fear of the moralist has not been justified. However, the economist is primarily interested in the habit of smoking and the consumption of alcohol in so far as they give satisfaction to smokers and drinkers and so generate supply of and demand for tobacco and alcohol. The economist is interested in knowing how many packets of cigarettes are consumed and to what extent an increase or fall in consumption could affect production, that is, supply. Similarly, he is interested in how much beer is consumed and how the supply of beer will adjust to the demand for it. He examines the habits and the pressures which can lead to the readjustment of wants and the reallocation of resources to cover the wants. <br/>  <br/> Some moral principles associated with religion tend to lead on to economic problems. Followers of certain religions are expected not to consume  <br/> pork, take alcohol or smoke tobacco. Devotees of some religious groups, on the other hand, can eat pork while others are expected to abstain from  <br/> alcohol and smoking. Strict observance of these moral rules could cripple the breweries, the cigarette factories and some businesses. However, there  <br/> seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers' a development which should be of interest to the economist. <br/> The view expressed by the writer in the last paragraph is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the number of alcoholics and smokers is certainly increasing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">more people now abstain from drinking and smoking</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">more people appear to take to drinking and smoking</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sales of alcohol and tobacco products have improved tremendously</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">It can be seen in this sentence  <em>However, there seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers</em>.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>15", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the Passage and answer the questions that follow.</p>  <br/>  <br/>  PASSAGE III  <br/>  <br/> Attitudes towards the smoking of cigarettes and the consumption of alcohol may be used to illustrate typical African ethics. Apart from the fact that smoking has now been linked with lung cancer disease, the African moralist has always regarded smoking as an indication of moral degradation. A number of people have accepted the moralist idea on smoking. <br/>  <br/> Some have refrained from smoking, and those who could influence others, such as parents and religious leaders, have also exerted their influence to  <br/> prevent others from smoking. On the other hand, a good many people have remained indifferent to the moralist view and have continued to smoke. The same argument has been applied to the consumption of alcohol. The African moralist, basing his judgement on the behaviour of a few alcoholics, tends to regard the habit of taking alcohol as a sign of wretchedness. The moralist holds the view that anybody who forms the habit of consuming alcohol will never do well in life. While this may be true in respect of a few people in the society, the fear of the moralist has not been justified. However, the economist is primarily interested in the habit of smoking and the consumption of alcohol in so far as they give satisfaction to smokers and drinkers and so generate supply of and demand for tobacco and alcohol. The economist is interested in knowing how many packets of cigarettes are consumed and to what extent an increase or fall in consumption could affect production, that is, supply. Similarly, he is interested in how much beer is consumed and how the supply of beer will adjust to the demand for it. He examines the habits and the pressures which can lead to the readjustment of wants and the reallocation of resources to cover the wants. <br/>  <br/> Some moral principles associated with religion tend to lead on to economic problems. Followers of certain religions are expected not to consume  <br/> pork, take alcohol or smoke tobacco. Devotees of some religious groups, on the other hand, can eat pork while others are expected to abstain from  <br/> alcohol and smoking. Strict observance of these moral rules could cripple the breweries, the cigarette factories and some businesses. However, there  <br/> seems to be a growing number of alcohol consumers and cigarette smokers' a development which should be of interest to the economist. <br/> According to the passage, the moralist idea is that</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">it is typically African not to smoke cigarettes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">people should accept a point of view only when they are convinced</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">smoking is not good but a little alcohol may be permitted</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the smoking of cigarettes is bad and unacceptable</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage mentions that 'the African moralist has always regarded smoking as an indication of moral degradation.' This implies that the moralist idea is that the smoking of cigarettes is bad and unacceptable, which matches with option 4.</div>", "topic": "COMPREHENSION PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>16", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/>  <br/> ...1...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">document </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">free </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">manuscript </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">quantum</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the term that best fits the first gap is 'manuscript'. A manuscript refers to a document that has been written by hand, or typed, and is often used to refer to a writer's original draft of a book, article, or speech. In this case, it refers to a speech that has been written out word for word.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>17", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...2...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a gathering </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a conference </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a congregation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an audience</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In the context of the passage, the term that best fits the second gap is 'an audience'. An audience refers to the assembled spectators or listeners at a public event, such as a play, movie, concert, or meeting. In this case, it refers to the people to whom the speech is being read.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>18", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...3...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">formal </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">genuine </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impromptu </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">guaranteed</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is describing a type of speech delivery that is reserved for very important or significant occasions. The word 'formal' best fits this context as it refers to something that is done in accordance with rules or a set procedure, typically for important or official matters.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>19", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...4... </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">conclusive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">critical </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">reportive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">speculative </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is describing a situation where the exact wording of the speech is very important or crucial. The word 'critical' best fits this context as it refers to something of decisive importance with respect to the outcome or result.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>20", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...5...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Negotiation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Organization </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Assembly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Audience</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage refers to speeches before the United Nations General ...5... . The United Nations General Assembly is the only option that fits the context. The General Assembly is one of the six main organs of the United Nations, where all member states have equal representation. It is where member states discuss and work together on international issues covered by the Charter of the United Nations, such as development, peace and security, and international law.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>21", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...6...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">polished </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">advanced </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">analogous </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discreet </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage refers to the speech being highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The word 'polished' fits the context best as it means refined or sophisticated. A polished speech would be one that is well thought out, carefully worded, and sophisticated in its presentation. The other options do not fit the context as well. 'Advanced' implies a higher level of complexity or development, but does not necessarily mean the speech is well-worded or sophisticated. 'Analogous' means similar or comparable, which does not fit the context. 'Discreet' means careful and circumspect, which also does not fit the context.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>22", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...7...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">anticipatory </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">profuse </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bifocal </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">vocal</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is talking about the inflection in the delivery of a speech. Inflection refers to the modulation of the voice to convey meaning. The word that fits best in the context is 'vocal', which refers to the voice or speaking.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>23", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...8...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interactive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">restrictive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">positive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">decisive</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is talking about the effects that could be destroyed by poor delivery. The word that fits best in the context is 'positive', which refers to something beneficial or good.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>24", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...9...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">language </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">slang </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dialect </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rhetoric </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is discussing the importance of the choice of words in a prepared speech. The term 'rhetoric' refers to the art of effective or persuasive speaking or writing, especially the use of figures of speech and other compositional techniques. This fits the context of the passage, which is discussing the effects of the choice of words in a speech. Therefore, the correct answer is 'rhetoric'.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>25", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">Read the passage and choose the most appropriate option for each gap. </p> <br/>  <br/> PASSAGE IV  <br/>  <br/> A prepared speech is not easy to deliver, especially if it is not written by the presenter. A ...1... delivery is one in which the speech has been written out word for word and is read to ...2... . This kind of delivery is usually reserved for very ...3... occasions when exact wording is ...4...,such as the State of the Union Address or speeches before the United Nations General ...5... <br/>  <br/> The primary advantage is that the speech may be highly ...6... in terms of word choice, turns of phrase, and development of ideas. The main disadvantage is that this type of delivery is difficult to do well. Reading aloud with meaningful ...7... inflection requires the speaker to be very familiar with the text. If not, the words will come out in a choppy, expressionless way. Such poor delivery could destroy any ...8... effects created by the carefully chosen ...9.... Lack of familiarity with the ...10... could also prevent the speaker from maintaining eye contact with people being addressed. <br/>  <strong>Adapted from Phillips, G. M. et al (1985), Speaking in Public and Private, Indianapolis - Bobbs-Merrill</strong>. <br/> ...10...</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">exchange </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">text </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">note </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">context</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The passage is discussing the importance of familiarity with the content of a speech for effective delivery. The term 'text' refers to the written or printed words that form the content of a speech. This fits the context of the passage, which is discussing the need for the speaker to be familiar with the content of the speech. Therefore, the correct answer is 'text'.</div>", "topic": "CLOZE PASSAGE"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>26", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question , select the option that best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</p> <br/>  <br/> In spite of his humble beginning, Audu now throws his weight around.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Audu is arrogant despite his simple upbringing</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Despite his obvious poverty, Audu is a proud man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">His noble birth notwithstanding, Audu is a corrupt man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">From his poor background, Audu is now a rich man</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'throws his weight around' is often used to describe someone who uses their status or power in a forceful or unfair way, which can be interpreted as arrogance. Therefore, the sentence implies that Audu, despite his humble beginnings, is now arrogant. This matches with option 1: 'Audu is arrogant despite his simple upbringing'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>27", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question , select the option that best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Ngozi has always considered her father to be an impassioned man.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Her father is a very lively man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Her father is an emotional man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Her father is a disciplined man</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Her father is a very strict man</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'impassioned' is used to describe someone who has or shows strong feelings or emotions. Therefore, the sentence implies that Ngozi has always considered her father to be an emotional man. This matches with option 2: 'Her father is an emotional man'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>28", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question , select the option that best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The elders rebuked Olu for taking issue with his principal.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Olu was cautioned for shouting at his principal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Olu was scolded for acting in collusion with his principal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Olu was reprimanded for arguing with his principal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Olu was blamed for issuing a statement denying his principal</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'taking issue with' means to disagree or argue with someone. Therefore, the sentence implies that Olu was reprimanded for arguing with his principal.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>29", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question , select the option that best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The manager paid us in hard currency.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We were paid in new notes</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We were paid in foreign currency</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We were paid in dollars and pound sterling</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">We were paid in a strong and stable currency</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'hard currency' is used to refer to a currency that is stable and widely accepted around the world. It is often from a highly industrialized country and can easily be converted into other currencies. Therefore, the sentence implies that the manager paid them in foreign currency.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>30", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question , select the option that best explains the information conveyed in the sentence.</p>  <br/>  <br/> If he went to London, he would see the Queen.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">When he goes to London, he will see the Queen</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He did not go to London and did not see the Queen</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He did not see the Queen when he went to London</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">He would like to see the Queen when he goes to London</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The the phrase \"if he went\" means that \"he didn't go to London\" and since \"he didn't go to London, he did not see the Queen\".</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>31", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p> <br/>  <br/> Only those who are <em>gullible</em> fall victim to his trickery.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">saucy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">devastated </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">courteous </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">astute</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To be gullible is to be easily deceived while to be astute is to to critically discerning or crafty.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>32", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> He is well known for his <em>inordinate</em> ambition.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">excessive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">passionate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">moderate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sound</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'inordinate' means excessive or unusually large. Therefore, the opposite of 'inordinate' is 'moderate', which means within reasonable limits.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>33", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Students could be <em>timid</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">friendly </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bold </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">covetous </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pugnacious</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'timid' means showing a lack of courage or confidence; easily frightened. Therefore, the opposite of 'timid' is 'bold', which means having a strong, vivid, or clear appearance.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>34", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The witness decided to <em>conceal</em> the evidence.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">divulge </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hide </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">destroy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pugnacious</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'conceal' means to hide or keep secret. The opposite of 'conceal' is 'divulge', which means to make known or reveal something that is secret.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>35", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The members of the congregation were <em>inspired</em> by the sermon.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bewitched </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enthralled </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disenchanted </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disorientated</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To inspire is to motivate, entrail or invigorate a certain belief or feeling while to disenchant is to free someone from a  <br/> type of illusion or feeling.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>36", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Agbenu was <em>ecstatic</em> about her result.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dispassionate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">sad </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pessimistic</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mad</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'ecstatic' means feeling or expressing overwhelming happiness or joyful excitement. The opposite of this would be feeling unhappy or sad. Therefore, the correct answer is 'sad'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>37", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The labour leader's <em>recalcitrant</em> stance was applauded.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stubborn </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">flexible </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uncompromising </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">well informed</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'recalcitrant' means having an obstinately uncooperative attitude towards authority or discipline. The opposite of this would be being cooperative or flexible. Therefore, the correct answer is 'flexible'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>38", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> A cool bath in a hot weather can be truly <em>invigorating</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">devastating </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unpalatable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">debilitating </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disgusting</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Invigorating is to impart strength, vigor or vitality. The opposite is debilitating, which is to lose energy or strength.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>39", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> I am <em>loath</em> to do the assignment.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">willing </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unwilling </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">waiting </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dying</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'loath' means to be reluctant or unwilling to do something. Therefore, the opposite of this would be to be willing to do something, which is 'willing'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>40", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Toyin is married to an <em>impatient</em>, self-centered man.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a fretful </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a tolerant </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an edgy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a tolerable</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'impatient' refers to someone who is not willing to wait or tolerate delay. The opposite of this would be someone who is 'tolerant', meaning they are willing to tolerate delay, hardship, or inconvenience without getting angry or upset. Therefore, the correct answer is option 2, 'a tolerant'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>41", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> <em>Gregarious</em> animals can be found in the zoo.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Various </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Wild </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Lonely </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Tame</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'gregarious' refers to animals that live in flocks or herds, i.e., they are social and like to be in groups. The opposite of this would be animals that prefer to be alone or 'lonely'. Therefore, the correct answer is option 3, 'Lonely'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>42", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The doctor examined the patient <em>painstakingly</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perfunctorily </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">professionally </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">painfully </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">carefully</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To be painstaking is to be careful and diligent while to be perfunctory is to do things without interest or  <br/> concern for quality.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>43", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The company has continued to <em>monopolize</em> the distribution of the products.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">centralize </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">specialize </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">liberalize </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">regularize</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'monopolize' means to have exclusive control over a commodity or service in a particular market, or a control that makes possible the manipulation of prices. The opposite of this would be to 'liberalize', which means to make something accessible to everyone, or to remove restrictions or prohibitions.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>44", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> A <em>conservative</em> estimate put the number of missing persons at forty.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A rough </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An accurate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A primitive </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An incorrect</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">A conservative estimate is an estimate that is deliberately low or cautious. Therefore, the opposite of a conservative estimate would be an accurate estimate, which is not deliberately low or cautious.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>45", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option opposite in meaning to the word(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The agency has sworn to deal with all the <em>apostles</em> of confederation.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">proponents </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">protagonists </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">apostates </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">opponents</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">An apostle of something is a strong supporter or promoter of that thing. Therefore, the opposite of an apostle of confederation would be an opponent of confederation, someone who is against it.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : ANTONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>46", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p> <br/>  <br/> The leader has the <em>unstinting</em> support of his party.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unsparing </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">laudable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">uninspiring </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cautious</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'unstinting' means giving or being given without restraint; unsparing. Therefore, the option nearest in meaning to 'unstinting' is 'unsparing'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>47", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The party supporters <em>vilified</em> the Chairman for the role he played in the crisis that rocked the party.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elected</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">challenged </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">condemned </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impeached</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'vilified' means to speak or write about in an abusively disparaging manner. It means to defame someone, to say or write very harsh and critical things about someone. Therefore, the option nearest in meaning to 'vilified' is 'condemned'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>48", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The company is to <em>shed</em> three thousand staff this year.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">demote </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lay off </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">throw up </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">placate</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'shed staff' in this context means to reduce the number of employees, often due to financial necessity. This is most closely aligned with the option 'lay off', which means to dismiss an employee, primarily for reasons that are not related to the personal performance of the employee.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>49", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> There was a <em>glut</em> of oil on the market.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a variety of </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an accumulation of</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an abundance of </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">an increase in</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'glut' refers to an excessively abundant supply of something. In this context, it refers to an over-supply of oil in the market. The option 'an abundance of' is the closest in meaning to 'glut', as it also refers to a large quantity of something.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>50", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> A few years ago, nobody would have believed that the economy would <em>turn around</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deteriorate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">improve </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">stagnate </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">change</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">To turn around is to to change an unsuccessful business, plan, or system so that it becomes successful.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>51", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> Before announcing his retirement, Ochima resolved to <em>settle an account with</em> the bank.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pay back all he owes </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">close his account with</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">retire his loans from </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">get back at</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'settle an account with' in this context means to pay back all he owes. It's a common phrase used in finance to describe the act of paying off a debt or obligation.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>52", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The boys knew that a storm was <em>imminent</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">possible </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">impending </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">threatening</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">encroaching</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'imminent' in the context of the sentence means 'about to happen' or 'impending'. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning is 'impending'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>53", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The nurse was in favour of <em>voluntary euthanasia</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a painless death </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a simple operation </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a sleeping pill </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a major operation</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Euthanasia is the practice of intentionally and painlessly killing a human being or animal for humane reasons.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>54", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The <em>cynics</em> feared that the nation's nascent democracy would fail.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pessimists </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">delinquents </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">critics </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">illusionists</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'cynics' refers to people who have a pessimistic view of things, believing that people are motivated purely by self-interest. Therefore, the option 'pessimists' is the closest in meaning to 'cynics'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>55", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The <em>essence</em> of governance is to seek the good and well-being of the majority of the people.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">importance</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">goal</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">characteristic</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">secret</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The term 'essence' refers to the intrinsic nature or indispensable quality of something, especially something abstract, that determines its character. Therefore, the option 'characteristic' is the closest in meaning to 'essence'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE INTERPRETATION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>56", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> From what she said, one may <em>infer</em> that she does not like the course.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">suppose </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">realize </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">deduce </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">agree</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'infer' means to deduce or conclude (information) from evidence and reasoning rather than from explicit statements. In the context of the sentence, it means that based on what she said, one can deduce that she does not like the course. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning to 'infer' is 'deduce'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>57", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> He shared his room with a person whose behaviour was quite <em>nauseating</em>.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disrespectful </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disgraceful </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">discouraging</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">disgusting</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'nauseating' means causing or liable to cause a feeling of nausea or disgust. In the context of the sentence, it means that the person's behaviour was quite disgusting. Therefore, the option that is nearest in meaning to 'nauseating' is 'disgusting'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>58", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The carpenter built a <em>commodious</em> wardrobe.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gigantic</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">small </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spacious </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wide</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'commodious' means roomy and comfortable, or spacious. Therefore, the option 'spacious' is the closest in meaning to 'commodious'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>59", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> Publishing as a business venture has become a <em>hot potato</em> in Nigeria.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unpleasant </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">profitable </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">unacceptable</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">expensive</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'hot potato' is an idiom that refers to a controversial issue or situation which is embarrassing or difficult to handle. Therefore, the option 'unpleasant' is the closest in meaning to 'hot potato'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>60", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option nearest in meaning toward(s) or phrase in italics.</p>  <br/> The man's story sounded <em>plausible</em> to his audience.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fantastic </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">credulous </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">credible </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">entertaining</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The word 'plausible' means 'seeming reasonable or probable'. It is used to describe something that is believable or credible. Therefore, the option 'credible' is the closest in meaning to 'plausible'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SYNONYMS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>61", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p> <br/>  <br/> 'I can't stand people prying into my private life', Ladi said. ...... agreed Agbenu .</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Me neither  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Me too  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">I also  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Likewise myself</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The phrase 'Me neither' is used to agree with a negative statement. In this case, Ladi is expressing a dislike (a negative sentiment) for people prying into his private life. Agbenu is agreeing with this sentiment, so the most appropriate response is 'Me neither'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>62", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The sergeant spoke to me in a ...... manner</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">coerce  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">coarse  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">course  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">causal </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct word to fill the gap is 'coarse'. 'Coarse' is an adjective that describes something as rough or harsh. In this context, it means the sergeant spoke in a rough or harsh manner. 'Coerce' means to persuade someone forcefully to do something that they are unwilling to do, 'course' refers to the direction or path that something is moving towards, and 'causal' refers to the relationship between cause and effect. None of these options fit the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>63", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The reason why he was not offered admission was ...... his results could not be found.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">because  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">when  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">owning to </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct word to fill the gap is 'because'. In this context, 'because' is used to introduce a word or phrase that stands for a clause expressing an explanation or reason. The sentence means that he was not offered admission for the reason that his results could not be found. 'That' is a conjunction used to introduce a clause expressing a statement or hypothesis, 'when' is a conjunction used to introduce a clause expressing the time after which or during which something happens, and 'owing to' is a phrase used to mean because of. None of these options fit the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>64", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Adika ...... a message from the club regularly.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receive  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">receives  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has received  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">had received </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The sentence is in the present tense and it's talking about a habitual action (something that happens regularly). In English, when we talk about habitual actions in the present tense, we use the simple present tense. For singular third person (he, she, it), the verb usually ends in 's' or 'es'. Therefore, 'receives' is the correct form of the verb to use.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>65", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Three quarters of the people in the village ...... killed but only half of their huts ...... affected.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were/was  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were/were  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was/was  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">was/were affected</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Both verbs should be in the plural because both nouns, \"people\" and \"huts,\" are count nouns.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>66", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> If you saw the photograph of the man, ...... you be able to identify him?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">can  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">will  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">could </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'would'. In this context, 'would' is used to talk about a hypothetical situation. The sentence is asking if, in the hypothetical situation where you saw the photograph of the man, you would be able to identify him.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>67", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> It is bad to take ...... property without permission.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">someone else's  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">someone's else  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">someone's else's  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">someone elses'</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'someone else's'. This is the correct possessive form to indicate that the property belongs to 'someone else'. The other options are grammatically incorrect.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>68", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> As Obande does not know anyone in this city, he hopes that some kind ...... will put him up for the night.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">men  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">individuals  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">man  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">inhabitants </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'individuals'. The sentence is referring to a specific person or group of people who might help Obande. 'Individuals' is the most appropriate term to use in this context because it refers to one or more people who are viewed separately from the rest of the group or community. The other options 'men', 'man', and 'inhabitants' are not as fitting. 'Men' and 'man' are gender-specific and 'inhabitants' refers to all people living in a particular place, which is too broad for this context.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>69", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Be careful not to ...... this money.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lose  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loose  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">loss  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lost </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'lose'. In this context, 'lose' is the correct verb to use when referring to misplacing or not being able to find something. The other options 'loose', 'loss', and 'lost' are incorrect. 'Loose' is an adjective that means not tightly fastened, attached, or held. 'Loss' is a noun that refers to the fact or process of losing something or someone. 'Lost' is the past tense and past participle of 'lose'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>70", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> How is the new editor ...... on with his work?</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">pushing  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">going  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">getting  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">moving </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'getting on with'. 'Getting on with' is an idiomatic expression that means to continue or proceed with something, especially in spite of any difficulties or interruptions. So, 'How is the new editor getting on with his work?' is the correct sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>71", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Nowadays, many graduates are not well disposed to teaching, ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">do they?  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">they are?  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">aren't they?  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are they?</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'are they?'. In English, when a statement is negative, the question tag that follows is positive. The statement 'many graduates are not well disposed to teaching' is negative, so the question tag that follows should be positive, hence 'are they?' is the correct option.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>72", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The armed robbers went into the house and robbed the three ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">women's occupants  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">women occupants  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">woman occupants  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">woman's occupants</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'women occupants'. The word 'women' is used here as an adjective to describe the occupants of the house. The use of 'women's' would imply possession, which is not the context of the sentence. 'Woman occupants' is incorrect because 'woman' is singular and 'occupants' is plural. 'Woman's occupants' is also incorrect because it implies possession by a single woman, which is not the context of the sentence.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>73", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> It is often ...... that inflation ...... from too much money chasing very few goods.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">say/resulted  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">said/result  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">said/results  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">say/result </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'It is often said that inflation results from too much money chasing very few goods'. The verb 'said' is used in the passive voice to indicate a general belief or statement. The verb 'results' is used in the present tense to indicate a cause and effect relationship. The options 'say/resulted', 'said/result', and 'say/result' are incorrect because they do not use the correct verb forms.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>74", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> If you would do me this favour, I ...... be very grateful.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">will  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shall  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">would  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">should </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'would'. In this context, 'would' is used to express a conditional mood, indicating an action that would happen under certain conditions. The condition here is 'If you would do me this favour'. So, the correct completion of the sentence is 'I would be very grateful'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>75", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> I have the ...... of meeting the President.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">privilege  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">priviledge  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">privelege  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">previlege </div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'privilege'. 'Privilege' is the correct spelling of the word. The other options are misspelled.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>76", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> My classmate, ...... I haven't seen for years, wrote to me last week.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">that  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">whose  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">whom  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">which </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'whom'. In this sentence, 'whom' is used as a relative pronoun to refer to 'my classmate'. The use of 'whom' is appropriate because it is used to refer to the object of a verb or preposition. In this case, 'my classmate' is the object of the verb 'seen'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>77", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Four weeks ...... for the police to conclude their investigation.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">has been  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">are  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">were  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is enough </div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct answer is 'is enough'. In this sentence, 'Four weeks' is considered as a singular subject because it refers to a specific period of time. Therefore, the verb 'is' should be used instead of 'are', 'were', or 'has been'. The phrase 'is enough' is used to indicate that the period of four weeks is sufficient for the police to conclude their investigation.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>78", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The woman is one of the ..... of the society.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elitists  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elites  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elite </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elitist </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">elite is the best option. The word does not take the plural marker (-s) in that context. <br/> one of the elites means the woman is one of the elite i.e she is  a member of the group of the elites <br/> </div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>79", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The doctor asked the patient what ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is the problem  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the problem was  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the problem is  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">is your problem</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'The doctor asked the patient what the problem was.' This is because in reported speech, the tense usually changes. Here, the doctor is not directly asking the question, but it is being reported, so the tense changes from present simple (is) to past simple (was).</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>80", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> He put ...... in a basket.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a white dozen eggs  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dozen white eggs  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a dozen white eggs  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">white dozen eggs </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'a dozen white eggs'. In English, when we talk about a specific number of items, we use the structure 'a/an + number + noun'. In this case, 'dozen' is the number and 'eggs' is the noun. 'White' is an adjective describing the eggs. Therefore, the correct order is 'a dozen white eggs'.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>81", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Idakwo ran ...... miss the train.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lest he almost  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lest he will  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lest he should</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">lest he may </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'lest he should miss the train'. 'Lest' is a conjunction used to express the possibility of something bad happening. It is often followed by 'should' and the base form of the verb. In this case, 'should miss' is the correct form.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>82", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Course ...... writers are to reflect local colour.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">material  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">materials  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">material's  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">materials' </div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The correct phrase is 'Course materials'. 'Materials' is the plural form of 'material' and is used here to refer to the things that are used or needed for a particular activity, in this case, writing a course. The use of 'materials' implies that there are various resources or components involved in the process.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>83", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> It was a free-for-all and the students were blamed for taking the law ......</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">into their hands  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in their hands  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">into their own hands  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">in their own hands</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">into their own is the best option. It means to do something illegal and often violent in order to punish someone because you know the law will not punish that person.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>84", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> Ali plays ...... violin with remarkable skill.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">their  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">some  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">a  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">the</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">In English, we use the definite article 'the' before musical instruments. So, 'the violin' is the correct usage. 'Their violin', 'some violin', and 'a violin' are incorrect in this context.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>85", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, fill each gap with the most appropriate option from the list provided.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The candidate's charisma should be a ...... factor in winning the election.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">determinable  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">determining  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">determinant  </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">determinate </div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Determinant is the appropriate answer. It means something that controls or affects what happens in a particular situation.</div>", "topic": "LEXIS AND STRUCTURE : SENTENCE COMPLETION"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>86", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same vowel sound as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p> <br/>  <br/> colon<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">e</span>l</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">gaol</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">colony</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">golden </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">girl</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">colonel /kɜːn<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ə</span>l/ and golden /ɡəʊld<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ə</span>n/ have the same vowel sound in the last syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>87", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same vowel sound as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> t<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">e</span>nd</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">jeopardy </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">turned</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">earned </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">caned</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tend /t<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">e</span>nd/ and jeopardy /dʒ<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">e</span>pədi/ have the same vowel sound in the first syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>88", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same vowel sound as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> mark<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">e</span>t</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">get </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">mortgage</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">enter </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bachelor</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">market and mortgage have the same vowel sound of /<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ɪ</span>/ in the last syllable.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>89", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different vowel sound from the others.</p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">dear </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">fair </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">bear </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">there</div>"], "answer": 0, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><strong>dear</strong> has a different vowel sound /ɪə/ from the others which have the vowel sound /eə/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>90", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different vowel sound from the others.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">hope </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">cost </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">coast </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">won't</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The vowel sound in 'hope', 'cost', and 'won't' is the short vowel sound /ɒ/ as in 'hot', while the vowel sound in 'coast' is the long vowel sound /əʊ/ as in 'go'. Therefore, 'coast' has a different vowel sound from the others.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>91", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different vowel sound from the others.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">naught </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">north </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spot </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">law</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">spot has a different vowel sound from the others. <br/> The other sounds are long /ɔː/ sounds but option C is short. <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : VOWELS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>92", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same consonant sound as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p> <br/>  <br/> co<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">n</span>crete</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">attend </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">anxious</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concern </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">consider</div>"], "answer": 1, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">concrete and anxious have the same consonant sound of /ŋ/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>93", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same consonant sound as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> <span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">ch</span>alet</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">college </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chemical</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chairman </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">champagne</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chalet and champagne have the same consonant sound of /ʃ/ at the beginning. Others have the consonant /k/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>94", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same consonant sound as the one represented by the letter(s) underlined.</p>  <br/>  <br/> tee<span style=\"text-decoration:underline;\">th</span></div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">though </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">taught</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">thought </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">tank</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The underlined 'th' in 'teeth' represents a voiceless dental fricative /θ/ in phonetics. This sound is also present in the word 'thought'. Therefore, the correct answer is 'thought'.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>95", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different consonant sound from the others.</p> <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">shoe </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ocean </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chef </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chief</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">chief has a consonant sound of /tʃ/ which is different from the others /ʃ/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>96", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has a different consonant sound from the others.</p>  <br/>  <br/> </div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">laugh </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">off </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">wife </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">of</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">'of ' has a different consonant sound from the others. The \"f\" letter in \"of\" is pronounced /v/.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : CONSONANTS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>97", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same stress pattern as the given word.</p> <br/>  <br/> cement</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">convoy</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">interest</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">perfect (adjective) </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">include</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">ceMENT and inCLUDE have the same stress pattern. This is the accurate answer <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>98", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, choose the option that has the same stress pattern as the given word.</p>  <br/>  <br/> typist</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">rebel (verb) </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">superb</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">refuse (noun) </div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">propose</div>"], "answer": 2, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">TYpist and REfuse have the same stress pattern. This is the accurate answer <br/> </div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : STRESS PATTERN"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>99", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"><p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, the word in capital letters has the emphatic stress. Choose the option to which the sentence relates.</p> <br/>  <br/> My MOTHER served rice and fresh fish stew for dinner.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What of kind of meal did your mother serve for dinner?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Did your mother serve rice and fresh fish stew for lunch?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">What kind of stew did your mother serve for dinner?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who served rice and fresh fish stew for dinner?</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The emphatic stress is on the noun MOTHER. The best answer will be one that has a noun different from MOTHER or one that asks WHO  <br/> carried out the action.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : EMPHATIC STRESS"}, {"id": "objective>English>2003>100", "question": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\"> <br/> <p style=\"padding: 3px;\">In this question, the word in capital letters has the emphatic stress. Choose the option to which the sentence relates.</p>  <br/>  <br/> The President SPOKE to the press.</div>", "options": ["<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Who spoke to the press?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Are these the press men that the President spoke to?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Did the President speak to the press?</div>", "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">Did the President write to the press?</div>"], "answer": 3, "explanation": "<div style=\"font-family:Cambria;font-size:17px;\">The emphatic stress is on the verb SPOKE. The best answer will be one that has a verb different from SPOKE.</div>", "topic": "ORAL FORMS : EMPHATIC STRESS"}];
